ive valence. As revolutionaries sought to rid France of its enemies, terror became associated with surveillance committees, tribunals, and the guillotine. By unearthing the tradition that associated terror with justice, magnificence, and health, Schechter helps us understand how the revolutionary call to make terror the order of the day could inspire such fervent loyalty in the first place-even as the gratuitous violence of the revolution eventually transformed it into the dreadful term we would recognize today. Most important, perhaps, Schechter proposes that terror is not an import to Western civilization-as contemporary discourse often suggests-but rather a domestic product with a long and consequential tradition.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aTerrorxSocial aspectszFrance. 0aTerrorzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 4aOld Regime (ancien régime). 4aabsolutism. 4aaesthetics. 4amedicine. 4apunishment. 4areligion. 4arevolution. 4asublime. 4aterror. 4atheater. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226499604423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226499604.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles